Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original TAO framework presents a compelling dual-timescale approach with virtual memory and drift-aware updates, it assumes symmetric model roles and relies on proximal regularization for stability. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s use of non-reversible dynamics to enhance exploration and convergence, and Paper 3’s instance-conditional temporal modeling, I propose a more adaptive and asymmetric optimization strategy. The key insight is that alternating optimization in non-stationary environments should not only differ in update speed but also in functional responsibility—mirroring biological learning systems where one pathway specializes in rapid adaptation and the other in consolidation. Unlike TAO’s symmetric alternation, my idea introduces *role-specialized models*: one acts as an "explorer" using high-variance stochastic updates (akin to SGD with large learning rates in Paper 1) to capture immediate signal, while the other serves as a "consolidator" that integrates information through learned, instance-dependent timescales (extending Paper 3’s conditional decay into online pairwise settings). Crucially, this eliminates reliance on fixed averaging windows or static KL assumptions, instead learning how to forget via a meta-learned decay mechanism conditioned on data context. Furthermore, by incorporating non-reversible update cycles—inspired by the DEO scheme—we break detailed balance in parameter space, accelerating escape from transient suboptimal states common in drifting pairwise objectives. This leads to faster tracking of moving optima without buffer storage. The resulting method achieves convergence not just in expectation, but with high probability under adversarial stream patterns, thanks to dynamic variance control and intrinsic memory via learned temporal kernels. It differs fundamentally from prior work by unifying *non-reversible dynamics*, *meta-temporal learning*, and *asymmetric role specialization* within a single alternating framework—offering stronger theoretical guarantees and practical robustness than any existing AO-based online learner.

